{"title_page": "LHA 120-N 55", "text_new": "[[File:The glowing gas cloud LHA 120-N55 in the Large Magellanic Cloud.jpg|thumb|LHA 120-N 55]]\n'''LHA 120-N 55''' is an [[emission nebula]] located within the [[Large Magellanic Cloud]] (LMC). It is a glowing clump of gas and dust that gets its light output from the hydrogen atoms shedding electrons within it.<ref name=howell/>  It was named in 1956, in a catalogue of [[H-alpha]] [[emission line]] objects in the LMC.<ref name=henize/>\n\nMultiple dense molecular clumps have been detected, at least fifteen of which contain [[young stellar objects]].<ref name=naslim/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=henize>{{cite journal|bibcode=1956ApJS....2..315H|title=Catalogues of H\u03b1-emission Stars and Nebulae in the Magellanic Clouds|journal=The Astrophysical Journal Supplement Series|volume=2|pages=315|last1=Henize|first1=Karl G.|year=1956|doi=10.1086/190025}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=howell>{{Cite web|url=https://www.space.com/32906-young-stars-highlight-galactic-superbubble-video.html|title=Superbubble! Young Stars Highlight Glowing Gas Cloud (Photo, Video)|last=Science|first=Elizabeth Howell 2016-05-18T11:56:23Z|last2=Astronomy|website=Space.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=naslim>{{cite journal |bibcode=2018ApJ...853..175N |title=ALMA Reveals Molecular Cloud N55 in the Large Magellanic Cloud as a Site of Massive Star Formation |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |volume=853 |issue=2 |pages=175 |last1=Naslim |first1=N. |last2=Tokuda |first2=K. |last3=Onishi |first3=T. |last4=Kemper |first4=F. |last5=Wong |first5=T. |last6=Morata |first6=O. |last7=Takada |first7=S. |last8=Harada |first8=R. |last9=Kawamura |first9=A. |last10=Saigo |first10=K. |last11=Indebetouw |first11=R. |last12=Madden |first12=S. C. |last13=Hony |first13=S. |last14=Meixner |first14=M. |year=2018 |arxiv=1801.01653 |doi=10.3847/1538-4357/aaa5b0 }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Stars of Dorado}}\n\n[[Category:Emission nebulae]]\n[[Category:Large Magellanic Cloud]]\n[[Category:Dorado (constellation)]]\n\n\n{{nebula-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:The glowing gas cloud LHA 120-N55 in the Large Magellanic Cloud (26505160923).jpg|thumb|LHA 120-N 55]]\n'''LHA 120-N 55''' is an [[emission nebula]] located within the [[Large Magellanic Cloud]] (LMC). It is a glowing clump of gas and dust that gets its light output from the hydrogen atoms shedding electrons within it.<ref name=howell/>  It was named in 1956, in a catalogue of [[H-alpha]] [[emission line]] objects in the LMC.<ref name=henize/>\n\nMultiple dense molecular clumps have been detected, at least fifteen of which contain [[young stellar objects]].<ref name=naslim/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=henize>{{cite journal|bibcode=1956ApJS....2..315H|title=Catalogues of H\u03b1-emission Stars and Nebulae in the Magellanic Clouds|journal=The Astrophysical Journal Supplement Series|volume=2|pages=315|last1=Henize|first1=Karl G.|year=1956|doi=10.1086/190025}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=howell>{{Cite web|url=https://www.space.com/32906-young-stars-highlight-galactic-superbubble-video.html|title=Superbubble! Young Stars Highlight Glowing Gas Cloud (Photo, Video)|last=Science|first=Elizabeth Howell 2016-05-18T11:56:23Z|last2=Astronomy|website=Space.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=naslim>{{cite journal |bibcode=2018ApJ...853..175N |title=ALMA Reveals Molecular Cloud N55 in the Large Magellanic Cloud as a Site of Massive Star Formation |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |volume=853 |issue=2 |pages=175 |last1=Naslim |first1=N. |last2=Tokuda |first2=K. |last3=Onishi |first3=T. |last4=Kemper |first4=F. |last5=Wong |first5=T. |last6=Morata |first6=O. |last7=Takada |first7=S. |last8=Harada |first8=R. |last9=Kawamura |first9=A. |last10=Saigo |first10=K. |last11=Indebetouw |first11=R. |last12=Madden |first12=S. C. |last13=Hony |first13=S. |last14=Meixner |first14=M. |year=2018 |arxiv=1801.01653 |doi=10.3847/1538-4357/aaa5b0 }}</ref>\